    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1909-01-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1909-01-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="853"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d853">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 2491/54–56.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Minister
                            <persName type="to">Squiers</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1909-01-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 30, 1909</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 153.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to department’s instruction to you of
                    the 23d instant, concerning the attitude of the United States regarding the
                    boundary controversy between Panama and Costa Rica, I have to say that the
                    present attitude of this Government is the logical consequence of its
                    instruction to Minister Magoon of April 16, 1906,<note n="1" xml:id="d853fn1"
                        >See <ref target="frus1906p2#pg_1201">Foreign Relations, 1906, p. 1201</ref>
                    </note> a copy of which is inclosed, not only for your information, but for
                    presentation to the Panaman minister of foreign affairs, in order to show not
                    only the constant attitude of the United States, but the necessity of such
                    attitude for the protection of the property interests of American citizens in
                    the disputed territory.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Bacon.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
